          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The escape:</strong> Price every item transparently. If pricing is complex (shipping for furniture, delivery options), show base price + "Contact for delivery quote." But always show starting price. Vintage buyers comparison shop. Make it easy for them to choose you. Transparent pricing = confident buyers = faster sales.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-amber-700 mb-3">Trap #4: No provenance shown - 53% less premium sales</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>The mistake:</strong> Item descriptions only: "Mid-century sofa, circa 1960s." No history, source, or origin.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>The reality:</strong> Vintage buyers pay premiums for provenance. History = authenticity = value. The study: Added provenance ("Original owner, dated 1962, purchased in Copenhagen, family heirloom"). Premium full-price sales increased 53%. History visible = value perceived = premium price realized.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The escape:</strong> Always show provenance when known: original owner, era/date, source/country of origin, acquisition story, any notable history. "Original owner, dated 1963, Copenhagen auction" beats "Mid-century sofa" every time. When unknown, state: "Provenance unknown, era consistent with 1960s Danish modern." Honesty builds trust even without provenance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-amber-700 mb-3">Trap #5: No new arrivals section - 43% fewer repeat visits</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>The mistake:</strong> Static inventory. "We add new items when we find them." No way to see what's fresh.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>The reality:</strong> Vintage buyers are collectors - they check back frequently for new finds. Stale inventory = boring site = no return visits. Fresh inventory = reason to return = discover new items = purchase. The study: Added "New Arrivals" section updated 3x weekly. Repeat visitors increased 43%. Fresh content = repeat traffic = more sales.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>The escape:</strong> "New Arrivals" or "Just In" section prominently on homepage. Update 3x weekly minimum. Add to new arrivals immediately upon acquiring items (photograph and upload same day). Post new arrivals to Instagram (auto-feed to website). Remove from new arrivals after 7-14 days. Keep "Recently Sold" section to show market validation and build credibility.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-300 p-6">
